long_questions.answer:
To handle both end-of-file and array-full conditions gracefully when reading an unknown number of integers into a fixed-size array, the loop condition needs to incorporate checks for both. A `while` loop is typically suitable for this. The loop would continue as long as the array has space (`array_index < ARRAY_SIZE`) AND there is still data to be read from the file. The `ifstream` object itself can be used in a boolean context to check if the last read operation was successful and if the end of the file has not been reached.

Example structure:
```cpp
int numbers[ARRAY_SIZE];
int count = 0;
ifstream inputFile;
inputFile.open("data.txt");

if (inputFile.is_open()) {
    while (count < ARRAY_SIZE && (inputFile >> numbers[count])) {
        count++;
    }
    // After the loop, 'count' holds the actual number of elements read.
    // Check if the loop terminated because the array was full or EOF was reached.
    if (count == ARRAY_SIZE && (inputFile >> numbers[0])) { // Attempt to read one more to check EOF
        // This means the array was full, but there's still data in the file.
        std::cout << "Warning: Array full, not all data from file was read.\n";
    } else if (inputFile.eof()) {
        std::cout << "End of file reached. Read " << count << " elements.\n";
    } else if (inputFile.fail()) {
        std::cout << "Error reading data from file (e.g., non-integer found).\n";
    }
    inputFile.close();
} else {
    std::cout << "Error: Could not open file.\n";
}
```
This approach uses `(inputFile >> numbers[count])` directly in the `while` condition, which evaluates to true if a read operation is successful and false otherwise (e.g., at EOF or if invalid data is encountered). The `count` variable keeps track of how many elements were actually read.

