"Unsafe memory access" refers to a situation where a program attempts to read from or write to a memory location that it is not authorized to access, typically outside the allocated boundaries of a variable or data structure. In C++, due to the absence of automatic array bounds checking, if a programmer declares an array of size `N` but then tries to access an element at `array[N]` or `array[N+k]` (where `k > 0`), the language runtime will not prevent this access. This can lead to overwriting other variables, corrupting program data, or causing a program crash (e.g., a segmentation fault).

**Example:**
```cpp
int myArray[5]; // Declares an array with valid indices 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
// ... some code to initialize myArray ...
myArray[5] = 100; // This is unsafe memory access. It attempts to write to the 6th element
                  // which is outside the declared bounds of the 5-element array.
                  // This memory location might belong to another variable or be unallocated.
```

